      <title outputclass="H4ForH3_1_9" class="- topic/title ">
         <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">9.406-4</ph> Period
of debarment.</title>
      <conbody class="- topic/body concept/conbody ">
         <ol id="d589e13" class="- topic/ol ">
            <li props="Runin"
                otherprops="H5_6abc123"
                outputclass="H5_6abc123"
                class="- topic/li ">
               <p id="d603e17" class="- topic/p ">
                  <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(a)</ph>
                  
               </p>
               <ol id="d589e23" class="- topic/ol ">
                  <li class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e27" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(1)</ph>
                         Debarment shall be for a period
commensurate with the seriousness of the cause(s). Generally, debarment should
not exceed 3 years, except that-</p>
                     <ol id="d589e33" class="- topic/ol ">
                        <li otherprops="i_ii_iii" outputclass="H7_i_ii_iii" class="- topic/li ">
                           <p id="d603e37" class="- topic/p ">
                              <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(i)</ph>
                               Debarment
for violation of the provisions of <xref href="http://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?path=/prelim@title41/subtitle4/chapter81&amp;edition=prelim"
                                    format="html"
                                    scope="external"
                                    otherprops="URLorEMAIL"
                                    class="- topic/xref ">41 U.S.C. chapter 81</xref>, Drug-Free
Workplace (see <xref href="FAR-i1094606.dita#i1094606"
                                    base="i1094606"
                                    outputclass="fm:ParaNumOnly"
                                    class="- topic/xref ">23.506</xref>) may be for a period not
to exceed 5 years;</p>
                        </li>
                        <li otherprops="i_ii_iii" outputclass="H7_i_ii_iii" class="- topic/li ">
                           <p id="d603e52" class="- topic/p ">
                              <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(ii)</ph>
                               Debarments
under <xref href="FAR-i1115334.dita#i1115334"
                                    base="i1115334"
                                    outputclass="fm:ParaNumOnly"
                                    class="- topic/xref ">9.406-2</xref>(b)(2)
shall be for 1 year unless extended pursuant to paragraph (b) of
this section; and</p>
                        </li>
                        <li otherprops="i_ii_iii" outputclass="H7_i_ii_iii" class="- topic/li ">
                           <p id="d603e64" class="- topic/p ">
                              <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(iii)</ph>
                               Debarments
pursued as a remedy under <xref href="FAR-9.109-4.dita#id188S90XE0V1"
                                    outputclass="fm:ParaNumOnly"
                                    class="- topic/xref ">9.109-4</xref>(d),
for a false certification regarding violations of arms control treaties
or agreements with the United States, shall be for a period of not
less than 2 years.</p>
                        </li>
                     </ol>
                  </li>
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e78" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(2)</ph>
                         If suspension precedes a debarment,
the suspension period shall be considered in determining the debarment
period.</p>
                  </li>
               </ol>
            </li>
            <li otherprops="abc" outputclass="H5_abc" class="- topic/li ">
               <p id="d603e89" class="- topic/p ">
                  <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(b)</ph>
                   The debarring official may extend
the debarment for an additional period, if that official determines
that an extension is necessary to protect the Government’s interest.
However, a debarment may not be extended solely on the basis of
the facts and circumstances upon which the initial debarment action
was based. Debarments under <xref href="FAR-i1115334.dita#i1115334"
                        base="i1115334"
                        outputclass="fm:ParaNumOnly"
                        class="- topic/xref ">9.406-2</xref>(b)(2) may be extended
for additional periods of one year if the Secretary of Homeland
Security or the Attorney General determines that the contractor
continues to be in violation of the employment provisions of the
Immigration and Nationality Act. If debarment for an additional
period is determined to be necessary, the procedures of <xref href="FAR-i1115383.dita#i1115383"
                        base="i1115383"
                        outputclass="fm:ParaNumOnly"
                        class="- topic/xref ">9.406-3</xref> shall
be followed to extend the debarment.</p>
            </li>
            <li otherprops="abc" outputclass="H5_abc" class="- topic/li ">
               <p id="d603e104" class="- topic/p ">
                  <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(c)</ph>
                   The debarring official may reduce
the period or extent of debarment, upon the contractor’s request,
supported by documentation, for reasons such as-</p>
               <ol id="d589e95" class="- topic/ol ">
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e114" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(1)</ph>
                         Newly discovered material evidence;</p>
                  </li>
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e123" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(2)</ph>
                         Reversal of the conviction or
civil judgment upon which the debarment was based;</p>
                  </li>
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e132" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(3)</ph>
                         Bona fide change in ownership
or management;</p>
                  </li>
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e141" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(4)</ph>
                         Elimination of other causes for
which the debarment was imposed; or</p>
                  </li>
                  <li otherprops="123" outputclass="H6_123" class="- topic/li ">
                     <p id="d603e150" class="- topic/p ">
                        <ph props="autonumber" class="- topic/ph ">(5)</ph>
                         Other reasons the <ph rev="FAC 2019-02 March 27, 2019" class="- topic/ph "><?FM MARKER [Why] Amend section 9.406-4 by removing from paragraph (c)(5) “debarring offical” and adding “debarring official” in its place.?>debarring <?FM MARKER [CaseNumber] Technical Amendments?>official</ph> deems
appropriate.</p>
                  </li>
               </ol>
            </li>
         </ol>
      </conbody>
